  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_459",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Improved Fault Templates of Boolean Circuits in Cryptosystems can Break Threshold Implementations",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Debdeep Mukhopadhyay",
        "email": "mukhopadhyay@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Fault Template Analysis (FTA) has been shown as a powerful tool for attacking cryptosystems and exposing vulnerabilities which were previously not reported in existing literature. Fault templates can be utilized for attacking block ciphers in middle rounds\nwhich were known prior to be resistant against\nfault attacks. In this paper we revisit the potent of\nfault templates and show a more systematic methodology to\ndevelop fault templates of Boolean circuits using a\nwell known concept in design verification, namely\npositive Davio's decomposition. We show that the\nimproved FTAs, called FTA2.0, can be used to fault analyze\nblock ciphers in the middle rounds using as few as\ntwo bit-flip faults. Further, it can be used to attack\nTI-implemented block ciphers by considering a\nDouble Bit Upset (DBU) fault in a target share bit. The attack shows that varying the latency of the fault the adversary can\nobtain unmasked bits and can recover the secret key.",
    "keywords": [
      "Fault Attacks",
      "Fault Templates",
      "Threshold Implementations",
      "Multiple Bit Upset"
    ],
    "category": "Implementation",
